<br>
The Vision (TM)<br>
<br>
The first major issue is that what VI and later SOE calls “The Vision” has changed so many times through the years noone really knows what the vision is anymore. It used to be known that there were soloing classes and there were grouping classes. The soloing classes could get good XP at the sacrifice of not being as useful in groups at higher levels. Likewise, grouping classes would find XP much harder to obtain but had the benefit of being needed at higher levels. This was the way it was – you chose your character with these attributes in mind. At some point the vision was changed. Some feel-good PC executive decided it was only fair that each class be able to log in and get XP in a short time by soloing or choose to group up and be desired in a long-term group. More about this philosophy later but this change in vision, I believe, is single-handedly responsible for a lot of the disparities we still witness between classes even though class balancing has been around for years.<br>
<br>
In the Beginning….<br>
<br>
VI created Norrath – they created the waters of the sea and the land and set the sun and Luclin to move above it. They set upon Norrath every manner of beast to kill to get phat XP and a wide variety of classes to play – each class distinct in its purpose and abilities. If you were around before the whole “class balancing” started, you would remember that each class was fairly well defined – Druids had nukes, ports and other spells, Shamans had slows, Mages had pets and nukes, Necros had pets and nukes, Wizards had nukes but better than anyone else’s…etc. Above this, each class had abilities and spells that were very different from each other. For example, Charm was the realm of the Enchanter as were mana buffs. Shamans were the kings of stat buffs. Necros could Lifetap. Mages had really wild pets. You knew if you chose a class that you would be really good at doing X but not be able to do A, B, C and D. With class balancing, that was about to change….<br>
<br>
Noone wants us….<br>
<br>
After a while, a cry was raised in the Druid and Ranger communities that their classes wasn’t very desired when it came to raids and guilds. They contended that their powers were so weak or so unnecessary that they were often overlooked for the holy 3 – Cleric, Warrior and Enchanter. The cry went up to improve their classes by granting increased effectiveness to their abilities AND new abilities. And so class balancing began…..<br>
My take on the subject is that the reason Druids and Rangers were finding themselves left out was not because they were designed so weak, but because everyone and their brother was playing them. Druids were always the Jack-of-all-trades class. They could do a lot of stuff but nothing really well – this appealed to many people right away, but when these people got higher in levels the fact that they were, infact, master of none really irked them. Rangers were drawn up to be the best class since sliced bread in the original EQ – track was such an appealing skill, I think Ranger was the #1 class people new to the game started. Sooo, with everyone playing Druids and Rangers, guilds had to put limitations on how many to take or end up being a guild full of Druids and Rangers.<br>
<br>
But I want to solo too…..<br>
<br>
From the beginning there were always solo classes and grouping classes. But at some point, someone decided that each class should have the ability to advance in the game by only committing a short period of time to playing and also without the help of anyone else. No matter that this went completely against the idea of an Online Multi-Player game where you would interact with others – I also feel that this was largely profit driven – to bring the game to working adults or busy people who could only devote an hour or two at a time to the game. So the idea was formed that each class should be able to solo to a certain extent and also be desired in groups. This was a change to the philosophy of many of the traditional solo classes and I feel really did more to disrupt class balance than it did to fix.<br>
<br>
I want it all…<br>
<br>
The idea to allow all classes to both group and solo well bred a way of thinking that would also make its way into each classes spell selection. For example – just recently, many people were complaining that, often, their guild or group was being held back by lack of Clerics (for the CHeal) and Shamans (for the Slow). For whatever reason, people weren’t playing these classes as much as others. So the solution was – instead of improving the abilities of those needed classes to entice more people to play, they passed these abilities off to other classes. Druids and Shamans got a gimped CHeal and Enchanters and Bards got a slow. To me, this seems ass backwards. You need more of class X in the game because of the abilities they provide so instead of focusing on improving class X, you just improve class Y and Z by giving them the abilities everyone needs. So you still haven’t solved any of the problems of why people aren’t playing class X and now you have 2 other classes that are even more desirable.<br>
<br>
This idea of “spreading the wealth” I think is the ultimate downfall of class balancing. Instead of having separate and distinct classes in the game that are valued for their unique abilities we now have classes that are almost exactly the same except for a couple things that make them special. Instead of balancing the POWER of each class to equal proportions and keeping them unique, they have effectively balanced each class to be almost exactly the same as one another in what they can do. Take pets for example. Used to be Necros and Mages got effective pets and chanters were just given a wimpy pet shield. Then Shamans were given doggy pets because everyone wanted pets back then because everyone thought they were cool. Later on, Druids complained and got their bear pet, later, Wizards complained and got familiars and their swords. Now, instead of having 2 pet classes that those who wanted a pet could choose from, now each class gets a pet – yay, pets are now not a defining factor for a class.<br>
<br>
My plea to Sony….<br>
<br>
STOP trying to balance the classes. That’s right – just stop. For a period of time, reevaluate the vision you have for each class – what makes it unique, what makes it fun, what makes it desirable or powerful. Once you decide this – run with it. Instead of seeking balance seek UNIQUENESS – each class desired because of its unique abilities. The POWER of each class must stay in balance but this can be done without creating classes that can do exactly the same stuff but on a sliding scale of who does what best. When I log on I want to play my Shaman, not my Shaman/cleric/mage/necro hybrid. If you want classes to be exactly the same just divide the world into 3 classes – melee, nukers and priests and be done with it. On the other hand, if you want variety, make each class unique again.<br>
STOP listening to customers and what they want out of their classes. Some people actually DO want it all – they are the ones that want to be the Fighter/Mage with Psionic Abilities and a Pet Tiger in paper RPGs. But this screws things up for the rest of us who accept our limitations and learn to live with them and enjoy the class for what it CAN do not what it CAN’T<br>
DO THIS NOW – before you get too far into EQ2. If I get into EQ2 and find the classes are the typical single player RPG characters that can cast spells, wield weapons and control pets – basically do it all – I for one am going to be very upset.<br>
