<br>
When EQ was launched, the class balancing was done with .. exp.  Warriors had no special abilities, nor was their additional hit points as big a factor as today.  Everybody was playing hybrids as a result.  Heck they were so slow to understand it that they considered the addition of berserker rage (which was not doing critical hits / crippling hits - just an added ability to hit mobs successfully which was and is still barely noticable) to balance.  Then they added critical hits, more hit points, higher skill caps, with kunark they added defensive (although we can safely bet that it wasn't designed to be such a class staple as it is).<br>
<br>
Necromancers were king.. groups of 5 necromancers level 20 could kill sand giants in Oasis because dots landed no matter what and the pets were tougher and faster to cast than today. They got nerfed big time.<br>
<br>
Rangers in kunark were really gimp as they had very very low defensive skill (forgive me can't remember numbers) and they were getting aggro too easily, which made them unable to tank, also had the same offensive values as warriors.. basically nobody wanted to play one. They increased progressively defensive, offensive, added jolts, etc. In fact they were so off track that at first they just added jolt..<br>
<br>
Lacking time atm to go further but basically all classes went through this, today's the result of all this messing around and I believe it's fun even if very very very different than the game back then.<br>
<br>
Just a fast correction: Enchanters always had slow, they gained the spell clarity though as a compensation for the nerfing of &quot;Whirl till you hurl&quot; - and back then only bards had mana regen ability. <p>--<br>
